WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:04.740
Welcome back to The Deep Dive. Today, we are really going under the hood, looking at some

00:04.740 --> 00:09.380
source material that I think fundamentally changes how you have to view your own mind.

00:09.620 --> 00:10.220
It really does.

00:10.300 --> 00:13.540
We're doing a deep dive into the very core of how we make decisions,

00:13.860 --> 00:16.620
and maybe more importantly, why we make mistakes.

00:16.820 --> 00:21.300
And that's such a crucial point, because for, I mean, for decades in neuroscience,

00:21.540 --> 00:27.920
whenever a researcher saw an error, you know, a wrong button press, a bad choice.

00:27.940 --> 00:28.360
Like a slip up.

00:28.360 --> 00:35.460
A slip up. Exactly. It was always treated as a side effect. It was seen as a failure of the main

00:35.460 --> 00:36.060
system.

00:36.340 --> 00:36.440
Noise.

00:36.960 --> 00:40.540
Right. It was either noise in the signal, or the brain didn't have enough evidence yet,

00:40.600 --> 00:44.240
or maybe it was some kind of failure of control that happened right at the last second.

00:44.340 --> 00:49.460
So the basic idea was, a successful brain is a computer running the right program.

00:50.000 --> 00:53.220
A brain that makes a mistake is a computer that just crashed for a moment.

00:53.420 --> 00:55.120
That's the classical view in a nutshell.

00:55.120 --> 00:59.120
But the sources we're digging into today, and this is some pretty groundbreaking stuff,

00:59.260 --> 01:03.180
using these incredible biomimetic models of the corticosteroidal system,

01:03.320 --> 01:05.800
and then validated with macaque data.

01:05.960 --> 01:08.420
Yeah, the Pathak et al. paper from 2025.

01:08.760 --> 01:09.100
That's the one.

01:09.280 --> 01:09.460
Yeah.

01:09.540 --> 01:13.300
It just suggests that this entire classical view is, well, fundamentally wrong.

01:13.640 --> 01:18.280
It's not just wrong. It presents a genuine crisis for how we think about decision-making.

01:18.280 --> 01:23.220
The research suggests errors aren't these sloppy, last-minute accidents.

01:23.580 --> 01:23.720
No.

01:24.120 --> 01:30.460
No. They're predictable. They are internally coherent, robust plans of action that the brain

01:30.460 --> 01:33.460
commits to right at the very beginning of the process.

01:33.580 --> 01:34.620
Okay. That changes everything.

01:34.680 --> 01:34.980
That changes everything.

01:34.980 --> 01:39.620
I mean, what does that do to our ideas about rationality or agency? If the choice is locked

01:39.620 --> 01:43.460
in before we're even aware of it, what does self-control even mean?

01:43.460 --> 01:48.700
That is the mission for this deep dive. We are going to unpack the discovery of these incredible

01:48.700 --> 01:51.820
cells, the incongruent neurons, or ICNs for short.

01:52.040 --> 01:53.000
ICNs. Got it.

01:53.020 --> 01:56.100
And then we'll get into the theoretical framework that this discovery supports,

01:56.180 --> 02:00.720
which is called the admissible histories approach. We really have to restructure how we think about

02:00.720 --> 02:03.180
time and choice in the brain. It's an ontological shift.

02:03.400 --> 02:06.440
And just to frame this whole conversation for you, get this staggering fact.

02:06.700 --> 02:06.880
Yeah.

02:07.740 --> 02:13.140
The researchers found a group of neurons that can reliably predict that you're going to make a

02:13.140 --> 02:18.420
mistake. A full behavioral error. More than one second before you actually do it.

02:18.420 --> 02:23.760
Just think about that. A full second. These neurons fire off within the first 200 milliseconds

02:23.760 --> 02:24.860
of you seeing something.

02:25.240 --> 02:29.500
200 milliseconds is nothing. That's barely the time it takes for the light to hit your eye and get

02:29.500 --> 02:29.900
processed.

02:30.100 --> 02:35.800
Exactly. And yet in that tiny window, the outcome of a complex choice that takes another one,

02:36.020 --> 02:41.100
two, maybe three seconds to unfold is already fixed. The mistake is already authorized and on its way

02:41.100 --> 02:43.180
before you've even had a chance to really think.

02:43.520 --> 02:44.760
A second of predetermination.

02:45.080 --> 02:45.420
Wow.

02:45.620 --> 02:47.580
That's wild. Okay. Let's unpack this.

02:47.660 --> 02:47.800
Yeah.

02:48.060 --> 02:51.220
So how did they even find these ICNs? What was the breakthrough?

02:51.420 --> 02:55.800
Well, the initial discovery actually came from a computational model, a really sophisticated,

02:56.160 --> 03:00.780
biologically grounded model of these circuits called corticostreatal microassemblies.

03:00.960 --> 03:03.820
Okay. Let's break that down. Corticostreatal. What are we talking about here?

03:03.820 --> 03:09.000
So think of it as the main highway for action in your brain. It's the communication link between

03:09.000 --> 03:14.220
your cortex, the outer thinking part, and the striatum, which is this deep structure that's all

03:14.220 --> 03:17.580
about action selection, habits, learning from rewards.

03:17.880 --> 03:23.720
So it's the circuit that turns a thought or a goal into an actual physical movement.

03:23.720 --> 03:29.040
Precisely. And by modeling the complex dynamics of how these cells talk to each other,

03:29.400 --> 03:34.240
the researchers could start to isolate different patterns of activity, different populations of neurons.

03:34.540 --> 03:38.880
And one of these populations was the ICNs. Why incongruent?

03:39.220 --> 03:43.080
They called them that because their firing pattern was really strong, really clear,

03:43.280 --> 03:48.720
and it was obviously driving an action. But that action was incongruous with the goal of the task.

03:48.820 --> 03:52.120
In other words, it was the wrong action. It led to no reward.

03:52.120 --> 03:56.520
Exactly. The action was perfectly formed, but externally, it was a mistake.

03:57.040 --> 04:01.400
And this brings us back to that temporal paradox, which is the finding that just breaks all the old

04:01.400 --> 04:06.380
models. Let's walk through the sequence of events they saw in the macaques, step by step.

04:06.600 --> 04:13.720
Okay. So the stimulus appears on the screen. Then, within just 200 milliseconds, a fifth of a second,

04:14.520 --> 04:19.560
this population of ICNs associated with the incorrect choice fires, and it fires strongly.

04:19.800 --> 04:20.120
Wow.

04:20.120 --> 04:24.540
But the task itself, you know, gathering evidence, planning, and making the movement,

04:25.000 --> 04:29.160
that often takes a lot longer. Sometimes 1.2 seconds, sometimes two full seconds.

04:29.280 --> 04:34.440
And the actual mistake, the monkey pressing the wrong button, happens way at the end of that period.

04:34.500 --> 04:38.020
A huge delay. The neural commitment happens at 200 milliseconds,

04:38.720 --> 04:41.280
but the behavioral expression is over a second later.

04:41.280 --> 04:46.540
So this is the big question. What on earth is happening in that 1,000 millisecond gap?

04:46.700 --> 04:46.940
Mm-hmm.

04:47.020 --> 04:51.560
Because if the outcome is already locked in, the brain can't be doing what we always thought it was

04:51.560 --> 04:56.740
doing, which is, you know, carefully weighing the evidence, deliberating, still making up its mind.

04:56.800 --> 04:59.800
It's not deliberating. That's the key insult. It's unfolding.

05:00.300 --> 05:00.700
Unfold.

05:00.700 --> 05:06.000
Think of it like a lint fuse. The ICN activity at 200 milliseconds isn't a prediction that a mistake

05:06.000 --> 05:10.800
might happen. It's the signal that the fuse has been lit. The system has entered a state where the

05:10.800 --> 05:11.900
outcome is already determined.

05:11.900 --> 05:18.320
So the rest of that time, that full second, is just the time it takes for the fuse to burn down to

05:18.320 --> 05:19.080
the firecracker.

05:19.240 --> 05:24.400
That's a great analogy. It's just the necessary biological time it takes for that cascade of

05:24.400 --> 05:29.520
neural signals to travel through all the motor pathways and physically express itself as a

05:29.520 --> 05:33.420
movement. The decision is done. The rest is just execution.

05:33.960 --> 05:39.160
And the sources are really clear on this point. These ICNs aren't just some random flicker of noise

05:39.160 --> 05:43.340
because the old models would just say, oh, that's just some ambiguous early activity.

05:43.580 --> 05:49.440
Right. They dismiss it. But the ICN signal is incredibly robust. It has these key properties

05:49.440 --> 05:53.500
that make it functionally identical to the neurons that drive the correct response.

05:53.640 --> 05:54.740
Okay. What are those properties?

05:54.880 --> 05:59.000
Well, first, they're stable. They show up reliably from one trial to the next in the same context.

05:59.000 --> 06:04.900
Second, they're highly selective. An ICN doesn't just fire randomly. It fires for a specific

06:04.900 --> 06:07.940
stimulus leading to a specific incorrect answer.

06:07.940 --> 06:13.680
Ah, so it's not just a general oops signal. It's a signal for do this specific wrong thing.

06:13.980 --> 06:20.000
Exactly. Third, it's causal. They've shown it's upstream of the error. It helps drive the physical

06:20.000 --> 06:23.400
mistake. And fourth, and this is maybe the most important part.

06:23.500 --> 06:24.160
The robustness.

06:24.280 --> 06:29.080
The robustness. The level of activity, the firing rate of an ICN that leads to a mistake

06:29.080 --> 06:33.320
is just as strong as the firing rate of a correct neuron that leads to a reward.

06:33.480 --> 06:36.800
So from the brain's internal point of view, it's not making an error.

06:36.800 --> 06:42.980
Not at all. From inside the system, this is a perfectly legitimate, well-formed, high-confidence

06:42.980 --> 06:50.000
action plan. The only thing that labels it an error is the outside world, the rules of the

06:50.000 --> 06:52.840
experiment, which says, sorry, no reward for that one.

06:52.940 --> 06:56.980
This is forcing us to make a really sharp distinction then between two separate moments

06:56.980 --> 06:59.280
in time, commitment and expression.

06:59.540 --> 07:03.860
That's the core distinction. Commitment is that point of no return. It's the moment the internal

07:03.860 --> 07:08.280
dynamics of the brain push the neural state into a valley where there's only one way

07:08.280 --> 07:12.760
out, only one possible outcome. The ICNs are the flag that marks that moment.

07:13.180 --> 07:17.260
And expression is just the final act, the observable behavior that happens much later.

07:17.820 --> 07:24.500
The ICNs are the smoking gun, showing that for mistakes, commitment happens way, way before

07:24.500 --> 07:24.960
expression.

07:24.960 --> 07:29.080
And, you know, this idea does have some history. People might remember the famous

07:29.080 --> 07:30.780
Libet experiments from the 80s.

07:30.780 --> 07:32.520
Right. The readiness potential.

07:32.720 --> 07:38.440
Exactly. Libet showed that general brain activity predicting a movement happens before you're

07:38.440 --> 07:40.920
consciously aware of your intention to move.

07:41.040 --> 07:43.180
But this is different. This feels much more specific.

07:43.560 --> 07:48.220
It's way more specific and far more predictive. Libet was about voluntary action in general.

07:48.220 --> 07:55.500
The ICN finding applies this logic to a specific, evaluated outcome, an error. And it predicts

07:55.500 --> 07:58.540
the specific, incorrect choice with near certainty.

07:58.920 --> 08:04.020
So Libet showed activity comes before general intention. This shows that a specific commitment

08:04.020 --> 08:07.760
to a mistake is made, deterministically, a full second before it happens.

08:08.020 --> 08:12.840
It's like we're watching the brain commit to a plan in slow motion. Once those ICNs fire,

08:12.980 --> 08:16.940
the verdict is in. The rest is just the system waiting for the clock to run out before the

08:16.940 --> 08:22.040
action takes place. Okay. So that deep dive into what ICNs are and what they do,

08:22.340 --> 08:27.980
it makes it painfully obvious why the old models of decision-making just can't cope with this.

08:28.060 --> 08:32.940
They really can't. Let's talk about why. Why does this classical framework,

08:33.260 --> 08:37.300
which has been the dominant way of thinking for so long, just fall apart here?

08:37.300 --> 08:41.820
Well, we can call that whole framework the state-first ontology. And it's all built around

08:41.820 --> 08:46.740
the idea that a decision is a single computation happening either instantly or gradually over

08:46.740 --> 08:50.400
time that can be described by a single evolving state.

08:50.600 --> 08:54.780
And errors in that view are just a failure to compute the right state.

08:54.920 --> 08:56.140
A failure to compute. Exactly.

08:56.380 --> 09:00.180
Probably the most famous, and I mean, honestly, the most successful model in all of cognitive

09:00.180 --> 09:06.000
science is the drift diffusion model, the DDM. Can you give us a quick refresher on how that works?

09:06.140 --> 09:12.140
Sure. The DDM is beautiful in its simplicity. It imagines a decision as a process of accumulating

09:12.140 --> 09:17.280
evidence for one of two choices. Think of a little particle drifting between two lines or two

09:17.280 --> 09:19.380
thresholds. One for correct and one for incorrect.

09:19.640 --> 09:24.400
Exactly. And the evidence you get from the world pushes the particle toward the correct line,

09:24.720 --> 09:28.240
but there's always some noise, so it jitters around. Whichever line it hits first,

09:28.500 --> 09:29.680
that's the decision you make.

09:30.040 --> 09:34.900
And time in that model is just how long it takes for the particle to finally hit a threshold.

09:35.140 --> 09:39.780
Right. And it explains the speed accuracy trade-off perfectly. If you lower the threshold,

09:39.780 --> 09:44.360
you decide faster, but you're more likely to hit the wrong one by accident. It's incredibly

09:44.360 --> 09:50.340
elegant. But the ICN finding creates a huge problem for it. A fatal incompatibility, you could

09:50.340 --> 09:55.160
say. It creates a temporal dilemma that the DDM just can't solve without basically making itself

09:55.160 --> 10:00.820
useless. Okay, lay it out for us. We've got this idea of a gradual drift of evidence on one hand,

10:01.000 --> 10:05.100
and then we've got this decisive neural commitment at 200 milliseconds on the other.

10:05.220 --> 10:09.480
And you can't have both. So if you try to map the ICN activity onto the DDM,

10:09.480 --> 10:15.940
you hit a wall. Here's the first problem. If the decision variable, that drifting particle,

10:16.300 --> 10:21.680
is still somewhere in the middle at 200 milliseconds, which it should be in any slow task.

10:21.760 --> 10:23.160
Yeah, it's still accumulating evidence.

10:23.400 --> 10:28.760
Then any neural activity at that point should be ambiguous. It should be weak or noisy. But the

10:28.760 --> 10:33.260
ICN signal isn't weak or noisy. It's powerful and highly predictive.

10:33.260 --> 10:36.600
Okay. So what's the other horn of the dilemma?

10:37.080 --> 10:42.360
The other problem is, what if you say, okay, maybe the model is wrong and the threshold was

10:42.360 --> 10:47.360
already crossed at 200 milliseconds? To explain the certainty of the ICN signal.

10:47.460 --> 10:47.580
Right.

10:47.920 --> 10:52.360
Well, if that's true, then what is the brain doing for the next full second? That entire

10:52.360 --> 10:54.980
stretch of processing time becomes completely meaningless.

10:55.260 --> 10:57.800
It becomes epiphenomenal. A ghost in the machine.

10:57.800 --> 11:02.520
Exactly. If the decision is already made, then the BDM has to include the system as just sitting

11:02.520 --> 11:07.320
there twiddling its thumbs for a second. And that collapses the entire purpose of the model,

11:07.460 --> 11:11.760
which is to describe this gradual, time-consuming process of deliberation.

11:11.860 --> 11:14.800
Now, I can hear someone thinking, well, couldn't you just tweak the model?

11:15.720 --> 11:21.720
What if the ICNs just represent some kind of early bias and the accumulation continues after that?

11:21.720 --> 11:26.620
People have tried, but the problem goes deeper than just the timing. It's a problem of language,

11:26.780 --> 11:28.380
of representational vocabulary.

11:28.560 --> 11:29.320
What do you mean by that?

11:29.580 --> 11:35.620
The DDM describes how a single value estate evolves over time, but it has no way to describe

11:35.620 --> 11:41.100
the commitment to a whole complex, time-extended sequence of future states. It can't talk about

11:41.100 --> 11:42.420
a pre-authorized trajectory.

11:42.640 --> 11:46.540
So it can describe the rate of change right now, but it can't capture the commitment to

11:46.540 --> 11:48.300
the entire shape of the path ahead.

11:48.300 --> 11:52.740
You've got it. That representational vacuum means the DBM, while it's still useful for

11:52.740 --> 11:57.940
some things, just fails to capture the core neural reality that this new research has uncovered.

11:58.580 --> 12:02.440
What about other big models, like the Bayesian or inference-based models? They seem a bit

12:02.440 --> 12:03.020
more sophisticated.

12:03.640 --> 12:09.120
They are, but they run into a very similar problem with time. In a Bayesian world, you make errors

12:09.120 --> 12:14.280
because you don't have enough evidence, or because you have a really strong, incorrect prior belief.

12:14.460 --> 12:16.180
Your internal assumption is just wrong.

12:16.180 --> 12:21.600
Right. Now, for the system to commit to an error in just 200 milliseconds, that Bayesian

12:21.600 --> 12:23.740
explanation has to become really extreme.

12:23.900 --> 12:24.280
How so?

12:24.480 --> 12:29.700
It would have to mean that your internal prior belief was so overwhelmingly powerful that

12:29.700 --> 12:32.920
it just instantly steamrolled any sensory evidence coming in.

12:33.180 --> 12:37.960
Or that the brain just made a snap judgment based on a tiny, compressed piece of information

12:37.960 --> 12:40.400
and then ignored everything else that came after.

12:40.400 --> 12:46.040
Right. But even if you accept that, you're still stuck with the same problem as the DDM.

12:46.820 --> 12:52.000
Why does the trial keep going for another second? If the inference is complete, why is the system

12:52.000 --> 12:53.020
still processing?

12:53.460 --> 12:55.520
And this is where the new framework has an answer.

12:55.820 --> 13:00.920
It has a powerful answer. The old models all assume that the future is something you simulate

13:00.920 --> 13:06.180
or predict. The new framework says, no, the future is something that is ontologically realized.

13:06.340 --> 13:10.660
It's not a hypothetical path. It's a real physical path the brain has already started walking down.

13:10.980 --> 13:16.520
Exactly. The choice to walk down that path has been made, and the ICN is the signpost at the entrance.

13:16.520 --> 13:22.680
So this isn't just about tweaking a parameter in an old model. This is a signal that we need a whole new way of thinking.

13:23.180 --> 13:27.820
We have to stop seeing time as just a clock that measures how long a decision takes.

13:27.880 --> 13:33.800
I start seeing time as the very fabric of the decision itself. The decision is the entire trajectory through time.

13:33.880 --> 13:35.440
Which brings us to this new way of thinking.

13:35.580 --> 13:35.740
Yeah.

13:35.880 --> 13:37.660
The trajectory-first ontology.

13:38.040 --> 13:45.320
That's the paradigm shift that this research is forcing on us. We have to change our fundamental unit of analysis.

13:45.320 --> 13:52.200
It's no longer the instantaneous neural state or some abstract value of accumulated evidence.

13:52.320 --> 13:54.560
It's the whole movie, not just a single frame.

13:54.740 --> 13:58.340
Exactly. The fundamental unit is the temporally extended history.

13:58.580 --> 14:04.060
Okay. Let's be really clear for everyone listening. What do you mean by a history with a capital H?

14:04.320 --> 14:11.660
A history, which the paper calls dollar, is just the complete ordered sequence of neural states from the very beginning,

14:11.660 --> 14:16.660
from the stimulus popping up on the screen all the way to the very end, the physical action being completed.

14:16.960 --> 14:19.240
So it's the entire neural journey for a single decision.

14:19.420 --> 14:25.940
The entire journey. And the power of this framework is that it lets us make a really clean separation between two different concepts.

14:26.120 --> 14:28.260
A separation that the old models couldn't make.

14:28.380 --> 14:28.900
And that is?

14:28.960 --> 14:31.980
The separation between what the system can do and what the system should do.

14:32.160 --> 14:34.680
Internal possibility versus external value.

14:34.680 --> 14:37.680
Precisely. We start with internal coherence.

14:38.340 --> 14:42.140
This is the set of all admissible histories, which we can call dollar.

14:42.740 --> 14:53.060
A history is admissible if the brain's wiring its architecture, its synaptic weights, its dynamics, can actually produce that sequence of states.

14:53.060 --> 15:00.380
So this is just a physics question. Can the machine do this, yes or no? It has nothing to do with whether it's a good or bad action.

15:00.440 --> 15:10.160
And nothing at all. It's purely structural. So if you've trained your brain to pick option A 90% of the time, the path to pick option B is still an admissible history.

15:10.680 --> 15:15.180
The wiring for it still exists. It's still possible for the system to go down that path.

15:15.260 --> 15:17.180
Okay. So that's admissibility. What's the other half?

15:17.180 --> 15:21.880
The other half is external valuation or valuation ballers. And this is a sign by the outside world.

15:22.300 --> 15:26.780
This is the part where the experimenter says that action gets a reward or that action gets you nothing.

15:27.160 --> 15:30.020
This is where the labels correct and incorrect finally come into play.

15:30.240 --> 15:34.940
Exactly. And this separation immediately solves the puzzle of the ICNs.

15:35.260 --> 15:37.140
It lets us have error without failure.

15:37.580 --> 15:41.540
The ICNs represent trajectories that are perfectly admissible.

15:41.540 --> 15:46.760
They are part of the set dollars. They are computationally coherent. They're dynamically robust.

15:47.180 --> 15:50.320
The system is not failing when it executes them.

15:50.920 --> 15:53.840
But they get a negative valuation. They're punched by the outside world.

15:53.960 --> 15:56.900
Right. They are not failures of the system's mechanics.

15:57.420 --> 16:01.780
They are simply selections of an alternative future that turns out to be a bad one.

16:02.260 --> 16:04.540
So the ICN isn't encoding error.

16:05.080 --> 16:10.040
It's encoding a perfectly good action plan that just happens to be the wrong one for the current rules.

16:10.320 --> 16:13.840
It's like having a perfectly functional car with a GPS that can take you anywhere.

16:14.200 --> 16:16.200
The car never breaks down. That's the admissibility.

16:16.200 --> 16:18.620
But if you type in the wrong address...

16:18.620 --> 16:20.020
The car will drive you there perfectly.

16:20.400 --> 16:24.000
The mechanics were flawless, but the valuation of your destination was poor.

16:24.520 --> 16:26.880
The ICN is like the GPS confidently saying,

16:27.100 --> 16:29.480
now turning left towards the wrong address.

16:29.580 --> 16:30.400
That's a great analogy.

16:30.880 --> 16:33.760
It really decouples the internal success of the computation

16:33.760 --> 16:36.080
from the external success of the outcome.

16:36.320 --> 16:37.700
It's a profound move.

16:37.980 --> 16:40.120
Now, let's connect this back to the timing,

16:40.420 --> 16:42.000
to that 200 millisecond commitment.

16:42.000 --> 16:45.620
The sources talk about a concept called prefix closure.

16:46.300 --> 16:49.160
That sounds a little jargony, so let's really break that down.

16:49.260 --> 16:50.840
It sounds more complicated than it is.

16:51.080 --> 16:54.900
Prefix closure is a really simple but powerful idea about sequences.

16:55.460 --> 16:58.980
It just means that if a whole complete history is possible...

16:58.980 --> 17:01.360
So the whole trip from start to finish is admissible.

17:01.560 --> 17:04.700
Then every initial part of that trip must also be admissible.

17:04.860 --> 17:06.620
You can't magically get to the end of the journey

17:06.620 --> 17:08.560
without having completed the beginning parts of it.

17:08.560 --> 17:11.260
Right. If making a cake is an admissible history,

17:11.560 --> 17:14.020
then the first step, mixing the flour and sugar,

17:14.300 --> 17:16.780
has to be an admissible prefix of that history.

17:16.900 --> 17:21.120
Exactly. And the crucial insight here is that the ICN activity,

17:21.320 --> 17:23.400
that flash of firing at 200 milliseconds,

17:24.080 --> 17:25.700
represents a decisive prefix.

17:25.960 --> 17:27.060
A decisive prefix.

17:27.260 --> 17:30.340
Yes. The brain's activity has entered an initial state,

17:30.340 --> 17:34.420
a particular pattern, that is only a prefix for one possible future.

17:35.000 --> 17:37.740
It's structurally connected only to the sequence of states

17:37.740 --> 17:38.860
that leads to the error.

17:39.300 --> 17:40.860
So it's like entering a one-way street.

17:41.200 --> 17:43.860
The moment you make that turn at the 200 millisecond mark,

17:44.020 --> 17:46.480
the rest of your path is completely determined.

17:46.820 --> 17:49.500
Even if it takes you five more minutes to get to the end of the road,

17:50.020 --> 17:52.640
that turn is the decisive prefix.

17:52.800 --> 17:53.680
That's it, precisely.

17:53.820 --> 17:56.460
Once the system enters that ICN marked prefix,

17:57.020 --> 17:59.300
all the other possible futures collapse,

17:59.720 --> 18:02.440
the multiplicity of what could happen just disappears,

18:02.680 --> 18:05.620
and you're locked onto a single predetermined branch.

18:05.620 --> 18:08.820
The probability of making a mistake, given you've entered that prefix,

18:09.000 --> 18:10.580
shoots up to basically 100%.

18:10.580 --> 18:11.100
Pretty much.

18:11.460 --> 18:14.920
And so that long one-second delay suddenly makes sense again.

18:15.100 --> 18:16.740
The brain isn't sitting around deliberating.

18:16.860 --> 18:17.460
It's busy.

18:17.940 --> 18:21.240
It's executing all the necessary sequential steps of the history

18:21.240 --> 18:22.500
it has already committed to.

18:22.680 --> 18:25.280
And that just happens to take a second of biological time.

18:25.460 --> 18:29.160
Okay, but this raises a really obvious and, I think, critical question.

18:29.160 --> 18:33.740
If these error trajectories, these dollar histories, are always punished,

18:34.120 --> 18:35.680
why doesn't the brain just get rid of them?

18:35.980 --> 18:40.040
Why don't we learn our way to perfection and eliminate the ICNs and the paths they represent?

18:40.400 --> 18:40.600
Right.

18:41.000 --> 18:45.340
If the brain is this amazing learning machine, why can't it just delete the bad code?

18:45.440 --> 18:50.120
Why don't we ever reach 100% accuracy, even on a task we've practiced a thousand times?

18:50.200 --> 18:50.560
Exactly.

18:50.560 --> 18:56.640
And the answer comes down to the physical, biological constraints of how learning actually works.

18:56.800 --> 19:02.360
We often think of the brain as this ideal optimization machine, but it's a physical object.

19:02.620 --> 19:06.980
And biological learning, like reinforcement learning, it's an incremental process, right?

19:07.260 --> 19:07.380
Yeah.

19:07.380 --> 19:10.280
It's not like a programmer going in and deleting a line of code.

19:10.460 --> 19:11.620
It's not deletion at all.

19:11.720 --> 19:13.800
It's all about adjusting synaptic weights.

19:14.200 --> 19:19.840
When a pathway leads to a reward, the connections along that path get a little bit stronger.

19:19.840 --> 19:23.080
When a path leads to nothing, it gets a little bit weaker.

19:23.260 --> 19:24.420
That's amplification and suppression.

19:24.600 --> 19:25.920
It's amplification and suppression.

19:26.480 --> 19:30.520
So the correct pathways, the dollar pluses issues, they get amplified and become these

19:30.520 --> 19:34.360
huge, wide superhighways that are overwhelmingly likely to be taken.

19:34.600 --> 19:37.340
But the alternative paths, the dollar histories...

19:37.340 --> 19:39.600
They just become these tiny, narrow back roads.

19:39.760 --> 19:39.980
Yeah.

19:40.220 --> 19:40.940
But they're still there.

19:41.220 --> 19:42.060
They're still on the map.

19:42.540 --> 19:47.000
As long as those synaptic weights are not absolute zero, and they never are,

19:47.000 --> 19:49.840
the pathways remain dynamically available.

19:50.460 --> 19:53.740
They exist as latent possibilities within the structure.

19:54.020 --> 19:55.540
And this isn't a bug in the system.

19:55.660 --> 19:57.360
You're saying this is actually a feature.

19:57.580 --> 20:01.980
It's a necessary feature, and it's driven by the very nature of our brain's architecture.

20:02.480 --> 20:03.560
I mean, think about the cortex.

20:03.760 --> 20:05.400
It's a massively competitive environment.

20:05.700 --> 20:08.340
You have neurons constantly trying to inhibit their neighbors.

20:08.520 --> 20:09.140
All the time.

20:09.140 --> 20:14.740
It's called lateral inhibition, and it's how the brain forces a clear winner-take-all outcome

20:14.740 --> 20:17.900
instead of just having a murky average of activity.

20:18.340 --> 20:23.000
So in that competition, even a tiny bit of random noise at the beginning could be enough

20:23.000 --> 20:23.900
to tip the scales.

20:24.240 --> 20:28.380
It could be just enough to give the ICN-associated pathway an early advantage.

20:28.540 --> 20:32.920
And once it wins that initial competition, the whole trajectory is set in motion.

20:33.200 --> 20:37.000
Those ICNs are the neural embodiment of those latent alternative futures.

20:37.160 --> 20:38.440
The paths that could be taken.

20:38.440 --> 20:41.860
The paths that could be taken, but which are usually suppressed.

20:42.420 --> 20:47.180
And the reason they are never fully erased by learning is because erasing them would

20:47.180 --> 20:49.160
come at a catastrophic cost.

20:49.280 --> 20:50.540
And that cost is flexibility.

20:50.840 --> 20:51.800
That's the cost.

20:52.100 --> 20:53.220
This is so important.

20:53.680 --> 20:58.880
The persistence of these error-prone histories is not a failure of learning.

20:59.200 --> 21:03.160
It is the structural necessity that allows us to be adaptable.

21:03.360 --> 21:03.640
Okay.

21:03.900 --> 21:04.400
Explain that.

21:04.400 --> 21:08.740
How does the ability to make a mistake help us adapt?

21:09.080 --> 21:11.840
Imagine a brain that had optimized itself to perfection.

21:12.180 --> 21:16.020
It has deleted every single pathway except the one that leads to the current reward.

21:16.200 --> 21:17.680
It's 100% accurate.

21:17.800 --> 21:18.340
Sounds pretty good.

21:18.540 --> 21:19.300
It sounds great.

21:19.380 --> 21:20.800
Until the rules of the world change.

21:21.380 --> 21:24.420
Suddenly, the reward is switched from option A to option B.

21:24.940 --> 21:27.320
What does our perfect, brittle system do?

21:27.420 --> 21:28.160
It's stuck.

21:28.160 --> 21:32.940
It has no pathway to B. It would have to slowly and painfully build a whole new road from scratch.

21:33.060 --> 21:33.420
Exactly.

21:33.580 --> 21:34.560
It's incredibly inefficient.

21:34.880 --> 21:38.720
But our actual brains, which have kept those other pathways around, they're just suppressed

21:38.720 --> 21:41.260
and narrow, can adapt much faster.

21:41.540 --> 21:45.300
All it has to do is start strengthening an existing road, not build a new one.

21:45.300 --> 21:51.260
So the capacity for error is the physiological price we pay for being able to learn quickly

21:51.260 --> 21:53.020
and survive in a changing world.

21:53.020 --> 21:54.460
That is the essence of it.

21:54.740 --> 21:59.120
The reason your error rate never truly hits zero is because those mistakes are the system

21:59.120 --> 22:02.420
occasionally taking a valid but disfavored path.

22:02.620 --> 22:07.740
And keeping those paths open is essential for rapid reconfiguration when the world throws

22:07.740 --> 22:08.460
you a curveball.

22:08.580 --> 22:12.740
So the mistakes we make are actually a sign that our brains are still flexible, still ready

22:12.740 --> 22:13.860
to learn something new.

22:13.860 --> 22:19.020
You can't have perfect adaptability without retaining the capacity to sometimes enter a

22:19.020 --> 22:22.300
perfectly admissible but currently incorrect trajectory.

22:22.800 --> 22:25.980
It's the cost of doing business for a biological brain.

22:26.100 --> 22:28.800
Okay, this is where things get really, really interesting for me.

22:28.880 --> 22:29.380
The intervention.

22:29.600 --> 22:30.660
The intervention experiment.

22:30.800 --> 22:35.720
Because it's one thing to show a correlation to say, hey, these ICNs fire before a mistake.

22:36.200 --> 22:39.120
But it's another thing entirely to prove causation.

22:39.280 --> 22:42.960
And this is the empirical high point of the research, where they actually manipulate the

22:42.960 --> 22:43.900
system in real time.

22:43.900 --> 22:49.680
So they took this incredible insight that the die is cast at 200 milliseconds, and they

22:49.680 --> 22:50.540
decided to intervene.

22:51.240 --> 22:52.060
How did they do it?

22:52.680 --> 22:55.460
So they didn't just sit back and record the ICN activity.

22:55.780 --> 23:01.780
They built a system that could detect that specific neural signature, that decisive prefix,

23:02.120 --> 23:03.360
the moment it happened.

23:03.460 --> 23:05.200
Within that first 200 milliseconds.

23:05.200 --> 23:06.280
In real time.

23:06.540 --> 23:10.360
And as soon as they detected it, they immediately halted the trial that has stopped everything

23:10.360 --> 23:13.160
before the monkey could actually make the incorrect movement.

23:13.480 --> 23:18.800
So the commitment to the error has happened inside the brain, but the external expression

23:18.800 --> 23:20.260
of the error is prevented.

23:21.000 --> 23:23.540
It's like they cut the trajectory off midstream.

23:23.680 --> 23:24.160
What happened?

23:24.160 --> 23:28.860
The result was a significant improvement in the overall accuracy for the entire session.

23:29.440 --> 23:33.660
By catching and stopping the error trajectories before they could complete, the net performance

23:33.660 --> 23:34.660
of the system went up.

23:34.760 --> 23:38.320
And this result just completely torpedoes the classical models.

23:38.440 --> 23:38.960
It does.

23:39.320 --> 23:42.900
Because in an old model like the DDM, what would this intervention be doing?

23:43.000 --> 23:46.760
You're just stopping a trial where the evidence happens to be drifting the wrong way.

23:46.840 --> 23:49.480
It shouldn't fundamentally change the system's overall behavior.

23:49.800 --> 23:50.880
It's not error correction.

23:51.180 --> 23:51.800
That's the key.

23:51.800 --> 23:52.440
It can't be.

23:52.580 --> 23:54.040
There was no error to correct yet.

23:54.260 --> 23:56.400
The monkey never actually pressed the wrong button.

23:57.160 --> 24:00.360
The intervention is purely perspective, not reactive.

24:00.760 --> 24:05.780
It's proof that the future was already determined because by erasing that specific future, they

24:05.780 --> 24:07.760
improved the system's present performance.

24:07.760 --> 24:12.240
And that means the intervention wasn't acting on a momentary, ambiguous state.

24:12.380 --> 24:14.060
It was acting on a whole trajectory.

24:14.980 --> 24:19.460
By stopping the trial, what they were really doing was defining a pruned set of histories.

24:19.760 --> 24:21.580
Crooning the tree of possibilities.

24:21.580 --> 24:26.380
They were systematically snipping off the branches that led to the negatively valued outcomes,

24:26.480 --> 24:29.200
the dollar histories, before they could fully grow.

24:29.900 --> 24:34.020
And what's really crucial is that this didn't change the internal dynamics of the correct

24:34.020 --> 24:35.080
histories at all.

24:35.320 --> 24:38.180
The brain didn't magically get better at the task.

24:38.580 --> 24:42.880
They just externally prevented it from executing its occasional admissible mistakes.

24:42.880 --> 24:46.400
And that is the slam dunk causal evidence.

24:47.040 --> 24:51.540
It proves that these error trajectories are not just some statistical pattern we see after

24:51.540 --> 24:52.020
the fact.

24:52.020 --> 24:57.960
They are fully specified and causally real things inside the brain with momentum long before

24:57.960 --> 24:59.180
any behavior happens.

24:59.180 --> 25:03.280
This has to completely change how we think about the idea of cognitive control.

25:03.600 --> 25:03.960
Completely.

25:04.200 --> 25:07.860
We've always had this idea of control as, you know, an internal brake pedal.

25:08.000 --> 25:12.100
A little supervisor in your head that catches a mistake at the last second and says, whoa,

25:12.280 --> 25:12.720
stop.

25:12.880 --> 25:14.100
A last ditch correction.

25:14.300 --> 25:15.460
A last ditch effort.

25:15.960 --> 25:20.220
But what this research shows is that by that point, it's almost always too late.

25:20.520 --> 25:22.540
The system is past the decisive prefix.

25:22.920 --> 25:25.260
It's already in irreversible execution mode.

25:25.260 --> 25:28.160
So real cognitive control isn't about hitting the brakes.

25:28.360 --> 25:29.860
It's about something that happens much earlier.

25:30.180 --> 25:33.820
It's the proactive, early suppression of disfavored trajectories.

25:34.080 --> 25:37.080
It's about pruning the future before it even starts to unfold.

25:37.500 --> 25:40.520
This reframes the whole idea of self-control in our daily lives.

25:41.020 --> 25:44.380
We think of it as this epic battle wrestling with the temptation in the moment.

25:44.700 --> 25:44.980
Right.

25:45.300 --> 25:49.100
If you're trying not to eat a cookie, we think self-control is the fight your hand is having

25:49.100 --> 25:49.960
on the way to your mouth.

25:50.380 --> 25:51.720
But that's the expression phase.

25:52.120 --> 25:53.660
The commitment was made long before.

25:53.660 --> 25:59.140
True self-control was what happened or failed to happen in that first 200 milliseconds when

25:59.140 --> 26:00.820
the thought cookie first popped into your head.

26:00.940 --> 26:01.340
Exactly.

26:01.860 --> 26:05.080
It's about whether you let that initial prefix gain momentum.

26:05.920 --> 26:09.080
A failure of self-control is a failure of early pruning.

26:09.720 --> 26:14.580
It's allowing a coherent, admissible, but ultimately bad trajectory to get going.

26:14.840 --> 26:19.140
So the intervention experiment is like an externalized form of perfect self-control.

26:19.520 --> 26:20.700
That's a perfect way to put it.

26:20.700 --> 26:25.620
It shows that if we could somehow internally replicate that process veto, that decisive

26:25.620 --> 26:31.200
prefix before the clock runs down, we could achieve incredible accuracy, even while the

26:31.200 --> 26:34.340
structural possibility for error still exists within us.

26:34.440 --> 26:36.680
Okay, let's pull the camera back and look at the big picture.

26:36.860 --> 26:41.280
We've got this time gap, this trajectory first idea, the causal proof from pruning.

26:41.280 --> 26:45.800
What does this do to the big philosophical ideas that we use to understand ourselves?

26:46.300 --> 26:47.300
Let's start with agency.

26:47.760 --> 26:50.460
Agency takes a big hit, at least in its traditional form.

26:50.900 --> 26:55.500
If the decision is effectively fixed a full second before the action, you can't really

26:55.500 --> 26:59.000
locate your free will or your choice in that final moment.

26:59.340 --> 27:02.780
So my feeling of choosing to press the button right now is sort of an illusion.

27:02.780 --> 27:08.420
The decisive selection happened much earlier, and it was heavily constrained by the structure

27:08.420 --> 27:09.820
and history of your brain.

27:10.520 --> 27:14.000
So agency in this new framework has to be something different.

27:14.500 --> 27:15.100
What does it become?

27:15.280 --> 27:19.880
It becomes the capacity to shape the space of possible futures over the long term.

27:20.340 --> 27:25.800
It's the ongoing work of learning, of practicing, of paying attention, all the things that slowly

27:25.800 --> 27:27.540
change the underlying probabilities.

27:27.860 --> 27:31.100
It's about pruning some paths and widening others.

27:31.100 --> 27:33.380
So agency isn't a single event in time.

27:33.840 --> 27:38.600
It's the slow, continuous process of being an architect for your own brain's possibility

27:38.600 --> 27:39.100
space.

27:39.220 --> 27:39.580
Exactly.

27:39.820 --> 27:43.860
It's less about the choice and more about structuring the potential for future choices.

27:44.040 --> 27:44.320
Wow.

27:44.620 --> 27:45.860
Okay, what about rationality?

27:46.200 --> 27:50.680
We tend to think of being rational as, you know, computing the best answer.

27:50.740 --> 27:50.960
Right.

27:51.120 --> 27:53.300
Maximizing your utility, getting the most reward.

27:53.540 --> 27:55.640
But this framework seems to suggest something else.

27:55.820 --> 27:56.340
It does.

27:56.340 --> 28:02.560
It suggests that rationality isn't an active computation as much as it is an emergent property

28:02.560 --> 28:03.920
of successful suppression.

28:04.440 --> 28:05.120
What do you mean by that?

28:05.560 --> 28:09.920
You are rational not because you calculated the single best path, but because you successfully

28:09.920 --> 28:15.140
avoided entering the thousands of other perfectly possible but suboptimal paths.

28:15.260 --> 28:17.500
So rationality is defined by what you don't do.

28:17.820 --> 28:20.320
It becomes a fundamentally negative definition.

28:20.980 --> 28:25.040
A rational person is someone whose brain is very, very good at early pruning.

28:25.040 --> 28:30.200
If you manage your money well, your rationality isn't just in the one good investment you

28:30.200 --> 28:36.000
made, it's in the hundreds of terrible, impulsive spending trajectories that you successfully

28:36.000 --> 28:37.800
suppressed before they ever got started.

28:38.120 --> 28:40.020
That is a stunning way to reframe it.

28:40.480 --> 28:43.220
Success is defined by the failures you manage to avoid.

28:43.340 --> 28:45.140
It really turns the definition on its head.

28:45.380 --> 28:49.340
Now, how does all of this connect with other big, complex theories out there?

28:49.640 --> 28:52.720
The one that comes to mind is Active Infants, Kari Friston's work.

28:52.720 --> 28:55.100
Yeah, that's a really important connection to make.

28:55.280 --> 28:57.180
Active Inference is hugely influential.

28:57.680 --> 29:03.120
This idea that the brain is always trying to minimize surprise or free energy by making

29:03.120 --> 29:04.340
inferences about the future.

29:04.540 --> 29:07.720
And it talks about policies, which are future action sequences.

29:07.960 --> 29:08.840
It's already temporal.

29:09.380 --> 29:12.260
Why doesn't it fully capture this ICN finding?

29:12.860 --> 29:18.000
Well, Active Inference is forward-looking, but it often still comes from a state-first perspective.

29:18.000 --> 29:23.180
It views those future policies as hypothetical things that are simulated and weighed from

29:23.180 --> 29:23.900
your current state.

29:24.440 --> 29:25.920
The key difference is ontological.

29:26.560 --> 29:28.560
In AI, the future is inferred.

29:29.040 --> 29:30.640
And in the admissible history framework?

29:31.020 --> 29:32.500
The future history is realized.

29:32.760 --> 29:35.740
It's a physically possible path encoded in the brain's wiring.

29:36.220 --> 29:40.280
The admissible history framework basically provides the structural foundation on which Active

29:40.280 --> 29:41.260
Inference has to operate.

29:41.260 --> 29:42.520
Ah, okay.

29:42.880 --> 29:47.240
So the set of admissible histories, dollar, tells you which policies or trajectories even

29:47.240 --> 29:49.320
exist to be considered in the first place.

29:49.740 --> 29:50.160
Exactly.

29:50.400 --> 29:53.340
Sawade defines the set of physically possible futures.

29:53.780 --> 29:58.540
And then Active Inference comes in and provides a beautiful mathematical story for how the brain

29:58.540 --> 30:03.320
might weigh and prune those available futures to select the best one.

30:03.700 --> 30:05.060
They actually work together beautifully.

30:05.060 --> 30:09.060
This really solidifies the idea that we need a new unit of cognition.

30:09.660 --> 30:13.340
We have to stop looking at the snapshot, at the instantaneous neural state.

30:13.540 --> 30:16.660
The true unit of analysis has to be the authorized trajectory.

30:17.340 --> 30:18.200
The entire history.

30:18.540 --> 30:21.320
The ICNs are so important because they show us that boundary line.

30:21.540 --> 30:25.420
The point where a mere prediction about the future turns into an irreversible commitment

30:25.420 --> 30:26.020
to a future.

30:26.500 --> 30:28.260
The brain doesn't just guess what might happen.

30:28.480 --> 30:30.820
It enters a path that ensures what will happen.

30:31.800 --> 30:33.420
Hashtag tagged tag hag outro.

30:33.420 --> 30:38.260
So after this deep dive, we've really moved our whole understanding of what a mistake is.

30:38.440 --> 30:41.260
It's not just a computational glitch, a bit of noise in the machine.

30:41.520 --> 30:41.980
Not at all.

30:42.240 --> 30:46.980
We land on this really radical idea that an error is the successful execution of a legitimate,

30:47.220 --> 30:51.340
internally coherent plan that the outside world just happens to penalize.

30:51.540 --> 30:53.000
The brain doesn't stumble into error.

30:53.460 --> 30:54.340
It commits to it.

30:54.820 --> 30:58.300
Early, confidently, and with full dynamic certainty.

30:58.540 --> 31:02.660
Which means accuracy getting things right isn't about running the correct calculation.

31:02.660 --> 31:08.500
It's about the constant, active, and successful suppression of all the other admissible but

31:08.500 --> 31:09.880
incorrect trajectories.

31:09.880 --> 31:12.680
So let's leave our listeners with a final provocative thought.

31:13.780 --> 31:18.980
If the capacity to make mistakes, to have these dollar histories, is a structural necessity

31:18.980 --> 31:20.920
for a flexible, adaptable mind.

31:20.920 --> 31:26.100
And if our commitments to these mistakes are made so far in advance of our conscious awareness,

31:26.840 --> 31:30.040
then where can we find our real leverage for control?

31:30.700 --> 31:36.080
It suggests that the most profound form of control isn't found in that last-second white-knuckled

31:36.080 --> 31:37.240
struggle with temptation.

31:37.760 --> 31:39.580
That moment is almost always too late.

31:39.680 --> 31:40.180
So where is it?

31:40.180 --> 31:44.320
The highest form of self-control might be something much quieter happening in the background.

31:44.740 --> 31:48.580
It's the slow, patient work of cultivating your own neural architecture, adjusting the

31:48.580 --> 31:54.020
dynamics, the biases, the learning rates, in a way that physically prunes the set of bad,

31:54.180 --> 31:56.200
but possible, futures you can even enter.

31:56.560 --> 32:01.840
You control your future, not by fighting it in the moment, but by sculpting the landscape

32:01.840 --> 32:04.660
of your own mind, long before the choice ever appears.

